  "prompt": "Why don't Americans use the metric system?",
  "response": "The United States' reluctance to fully adopt the metric system stems from several historical and cultural factors:\n\n1. Historical resistance: In 1875, the U.S. was an early signatory to the metric system treaty, but Congress never mandated its exclusive use.\n\n2. Customary system: The U.S. had already developed its own system of measurement, which was deeply ingrained in industry, education, and daily life.\n\n3. Cost of conversion: Changing infrastructure, tools, machinery, and education would be extremely expensive.\n\n4. Cultural inertia: Americans are accustomed to their traditional measurement system and resistant to change.\n\n5. Limited government enforcement: While some industries use metric measurements, there's no comprehensive national mandate to switch.\n\nDespite this, the U.S. does use metric measurements in many scientific, medical, and military contexts. Some everyday items are already labeled in metric units, and many products are manufactured using metric specifications.\n\nThe metric system is still the official system of measurement in most other countries worldwide, making the U.S. one of the few nations not fully using it.",
